title: Drop legacy `_shN` JST syntax and make `sh` a boolean; preserve `jstN_sh` pin-count form
description: Removes legacy support for _shnumber forms, making sh a boolean and preserving pin-count derivation from jstN_sh or num_pins parameter.
body:
### Motivation
- Remove legacy support for `_sh${number}` forms so `sh` behaves like other boolean footprint options and no longer carries a numeric pin-count. 
- Keep pin-count derivation coming from the canonical `jst${N}_sh` footprint or an explicit `num_pins` parameter. 

### Description
- Make `sh` strictly a boolean in the JST Zod schema by changing it to `z.boolean().optional()` and remove the numeric/string transform that interpreted `_shN`. 
- Parse explicit SH pin counts from the footprint string using the `jst(\d+)_sh` pattern and from an explicit `num_pins` in `raw_params`, and remove the fallback that read a numeric `sh` value. 
- Remove stray `console.log` debug lines in SH pad generation. 
- Update tests in `tests/jst.test.ts` to use `jst8_sh`/`jst2_sh` and `jst6_sh`, add a `jst_sh6_is_invalid` assertion for the removed `_shN` form, and regenerate SVG snapshots (renamed snapshot files replacing the legacy `_shN` variants). 

### Testing
- Ran `BUN_UPDATE_SNAPSHOTS=1 bun test tests/jst.test.ts` to regenerate snapshots and the run passed. 
- Ran `bun test tests/jst.test.ts` which passed all updated JST tests. 
- Ran `bun run format` which completed successfully. 
- Ran `bunx tsc --noEmit` which failed due to pre-existing repository-wide TypeScript errors unrelated to these JST changes.

title: Fix chip pcb calc(board.*) resolution timing
description: Fixes errors caused by premature evaluation of pcbXpcbY calculations for chips before they are attached to a board, ensuring correct placement and avoiding creation errors.
body:
### Motivation
- Avoid evaluating `pcbX`/`pcbY` calc expressions that reference `board.*` before the `chip` is attached to a `board`, which caused errors like `Cannot resolve pcbX for Chip: no board found for board.* variables`.
- Ensure board-bound `calc(...)` expressions are only evaluated at PCB placement time where board variables are available.

### Description
- Removed eager calls to `getResolvedPcbPositionProp()` from `Chip.initPorts` so port initialization no longer forces pcb coordinate evaluation.
- Removed an unused `getResolvedPcbPositionProp()` call from `Chip.doInitialSourceRender` to avoid premature pcb position resolution.
- Added a focused regression test `tests/components/pcb/calc-pcb-position-chip.test.tsx` that places a `<chip>` on a `20mm x 10mm` board with `pcbX="calc(board.maxx - 1mm)"` and asserts placement and absence of creation errors.

### Testing
- Ran the new regression test with `bun test tests/components/pcb/calc-pcb-position-chip.test.tsx` and it passed.
- Re-ran the existing calc tests with `bun test tests/components/pcb/calc-pcb-position.test.tsx` and they passed.
- Typechecked the project with `bunx tsc --noEmit` which completed successfully and formatted the repo with `bun run format`.

title: Handle node_modules @tsci CAD asset paths in 3D viewer resolution
description: Normalizes CAD asset URLs in circuit JSON to correctly fetch assets from the package registry instead of treating them as same-package files.
body:
### Motivation
- CAD asset URLs in circuit JSON may point into `node_modules/@tsci/...` (for example `./node_modules/@tsci/imrishabh18.library/...`) and must be fetched from the package registry rather than treated as same-package files. 
- The resolver needs to normalize an optional `./` prefix and map external `@tsci` package paths into `package_files/download` lookup parameters so `CadViewer` can load those assets.

### Description
- Added `NODE_MODULES_TSCI_PACKAGE_ASSET_REGEX` to detect `node_modules/@tsci/...` style asset references and `normalizeAssetPath` to strip a leading `./`.
- Implemented `getPackageFileLookupParams` which returns a `Record<string,string> | null` describing the correct lookup params for `package_files/download` for external `@tsci` assets, `package_release_id` lookups, or current-author package lookups.
- Updated the asset fetch loop to use `getPackageFileLookupParams`, construct `URLSearchParams` from its return value, and skip assets without lookup params.
- Store fetched blob URLs in the map under both the original `assetUrl` and the normalized path (without `./`) so `resolveStaticAsset` can resolve either form passed to the `CadViewer`.

### Testing
- Ran TypeScript type-checking with `bun run typecheck`, which completed successfully.

### Motivation

### Description
- Introduced `MountedBoardChipProps` and merged it into `MountedBoardProps` so mounted boards expose selected chip fields such as `manufacturerPartNumber`, `pinLabels`, `showPinAliases`, `pcbPinLabels`, `schPortArrangement`, `pinCompatibleVariants`, `noSchematicRepresentation`, `internallyConnectedPins`, and `externallyConnectedPins`.
- Wired `mountedboardProps` to validate the new fields by referencing `chipProps.shape.*` to reuse the chip zod validators.
- Added `tests/mountedboard.test.ts` with parsing assertions for footprint/common layout props and the newly-supported chip-compatible props.

title: Unify PCB Texture Pipeline: Replace Per-Layer Meshes with Combined Board Textures and Centralized Visibility Control
description: Replaces fragmented per-layer texture system with a unified combined board texture pipeline, centralizing texture generation and visibility control, while reducing scene complexity and improving performance.
body:
This PR overhauls the 3D PCB texture architecture by replacing the fragmented per-layer texture system with a unified combined board texture pipeline. Individual trace, soldermask, silkscreen, copper text, pour, and panel outline meshes are removed and composited into a single top and bottom board texture via createCombinedBoardTextures.

Texture generation is now centralized and visibility-aware, eliminating manual mesh toggling logic and reducing scene complexity. useManifoldBoardBuilder is simplified to focus purely on geometry, while texture creation moves into a dedicated combined texture layer driven by LayerVisibilityState.

The Three.js rendering layer now creates only one texture plane per board side, improving render determinism, reducing z-fighting, and significantly lowering mesh count. Explicit texture and material disposal is introduced to prevent GPU memory leaks.

Result: cleaner architecture, fewer meshes, visibility-driven texture composition, improved performance, and safer WebGL resource management.

title: Fix pcbnotedimension anchors for calc-based edge positioning
description: Fixes incorrect positioning of pcb note dimensions that reference components via selector when components are positioned using calc-based edge anchors, ensuring accurate rendering after PCB layout.
body:
### Motivation

- pcb note dimensions that reference components via selector were resolving to pre-layout transform positions and collapsed when components were positioned via `calc(...)` edge anchors.
- The intent is for selector-based `pcbnotedimension` endpoints to reflect the final placed positions from the circuit JSON so notes/dimensions render correctly after PCB layout.

### Description

- Prefer final placed positions by resolving a selector target's `pcb_component.center` from the circuit DB when available inside `_resolvePoint` in `PcbNoteDimension`. 
- Fall back to the previous pre-layout transform position when no placed `pcb_component.center` is present. 
- Add `doInitialPcbLayout` to `PcbNoteDimension` to recompute and persist the `from`/`to` points after PCB layout runs so note dimensions follow final placement. 
- Strengthen `tests/components/pcb/pcb-edge-positioning-with-calc-and-notes.test.tsx` to assert that the `pcb_note_dimension` endpoints match component centers for both X and Y edge-anchor cases and update the PCB SVG snapshot accordingly.

### Testing

- Ran `bun test tests/components/pcb/pcb-edge-positioning-with-calc-and-notes.test.tsx` and updated SVG snapshot with `BUN_UPDATE_SNAPSHOTS=1`, which passed. 
- Ran `bun test tests/components/primitive-components/pcb-note-dimension-using-selector.test.tsx tests/components/primitive-components/pcb-note-dimension-board.test.tsx`, both passed.

The soldermask is now rendered on an isolated canvas layer, openings are subtracted using destination-out, and negative margins correctly generate mask-over-copper rings. Holes, plated holes, vias, SMT pads, traces, and cutouts now cut clean geometric openings rather than relying on substrate/copper color overlays. Rendering order in CircuitToCanvasDrawer was adjusted so mask-aware elements are processed before compositing, and the soldermask layer is merged back onto the main canvas deterministically. Snapshot tests were updated to reflect the physically accurate mask subtraction model and explicit board material rendering.

title: Improve user-facing DRC messages: hide internal IDs and add reposition guidance
description: User-facing DRC messages now avoid exposing internal circuit-json IDs and provide actionable guidance for layout issues, enhancing clarity and usability for end users.
body:
### Motivation
- User-facing DRC messages must not leak internal circuit-json IDs (e.g. `pcb_component_id`, `pcb_port_id`) because they are meaningless to end users and noisy in logs. 
- Error messages should be more actionable by offering guidance to fix layout problems (e.g. how far and in which direction to move a component). 
- Tests should assert that readable messages are used and that raw IDs are not present in user-facing text. 

### Description
- Added `lib/util/get-readable-names.ts` implementing `getReadableNameForComponent`, `getReadableNameForPort`, `getReadableNameForElementId`, `getReadableNameForGroup`, and `containsCircuitJsonId`, which wrap `@tscircuit/circuit-json-util` and sanitize candidates to avoid exposing raw IDs. 
- Updated `checkEachPcbPortConnectedToPcbTraces` to use `getReadableNameForPort` when constructing the message so it shows friendly port labels instead of raw `pcb_port_id`. 
- Updated `checkPcbComponentOverlap` to use `getReadableNameForElementId` in overlap messages so element labels are human-readable. 
- Updated `checkSourceTracesHavePcbTraces` to avoid showing a `source_trace` display name when that name looks like an internal ID, falling back to a neutral label. 
- Enhanced `checkPcbComponentsOutOfBoard` to use `getReadableNameForComponent` and added a `getRepositionSuggestion` helper that computes a direction and approximate mm offset and appends an actionable suggestion to the message while preserving structured IDs in the error object. 
- Restored and updated tests: `tests/lib/check-each-pcb-port-connected.test.ts` now uses inline snapshots reflecting the readable message shape and asserts `containsCircuitJsonId` is false, and `tests/lib/run-all-checks.test.ts` includes a test ensuring error messages never expose circuit-json IDs. 

### Testing

body:
This pull request introduces support for rendering a "faux board" when a circuit JSON lacks a `pcb_board` or `pcb_panel` entry. This feature ensures that 3D scenes and GLTF exports always include a board-like geometry, improving robustness and visualization for incomplete circuit descriptions. The implementation includes configurable options, core logic changes, and new tests to verify the feature.

**Faux board rendering support:**

* Added `drawFauxBoard` option to `ConversionOptions` and `CircuitTo3DOptions` types, allowing users to request a fallback board when no real board or panel is present. title: Improve PCB port connectivity error messages by preferring source component/port names
description: Updates error messages for PCB port connectivity to use human-readable names derived from source components and ports instead of generic labels.
body:
### Motivation
- Error messages that reported ports as generic labels like `port` or exposed circuit-json ids were unhelpful to users; the goal is to emit human-readable port names that point to the corresponding source component and source port when available.
- Mapping a `pcb_port` back to its `source_port` and `source_component` usually yields the best, actionable label (for example `U1.A`), so the checks should prefer that information.

### Description
- Update `getReadableNameForPort` to locate the `pcb_port` in the soup and, if present, resolve its `source_port` and `source_component` to derive a readable name in the form `Component.Port` or fallback to `Port`-level names. (file: `lib/util/get-readable-names.ts`)
- Add a small helper `firstReadableName` to pick the first usable candidate from a list (used to prefer source `name`, then `pin_number`, then `port_hints`).
- Add a regression test that reproduces the old poor message and asserts the improved labeling (`Ports [U1.A, R5.K] ...`) and update one snapshot expectation to reflect the improved numeric fallback (`1, 2`) when component names are not available. (file: `tests/lib/check-each-pcb-port-connected.test.ts`)
- Preserve existing fallback behavior to the previous `getReadableNameForPcbPort`/`getReadableNameForElement` logic when no source-level naming can be resolved.

### Testing
- Ran `bun test tests/lib/check-each-pcb-port-connected.test.ts tests/lib/run-all-checks.test.ts` and all tests passed after the change (previous failing snapshot was updated to match new behavior). 
- Ran TypeScript type-check with `bunx tsc --noEmit` which completed successfully. 
- Ran formatter with `bun run format` which completed but reported configured file-size warnings for large fixtures (format succeeded otherwise).

title: Fix Validation Flaw: Enforce Strict NumberOnly Input in Settings and Remove Native Browser Spinners
description: Enforces strict number-only validation for input fields, blocking alphabetic characters and scientific notation while allowing decimals and conditional negatives, and removes native browser spinner controls for a cleaner UI.
body:
This PR hardens the input layer by enforcing strict numberonly validation, blocking alphabetic characters and scientific notation, while preserving support for decimals and conditional negatives. It also removes native browser spinner controls for a cleaner, more consistent UI.
The result is stronger validation integrity, improved user experience, and consistent numeric behavior across all laser and advanced settings fields.

body:
Refactored the footer to remove non-functional <Link> components and replace them with styled <span> elements while preserving layout and design consistency.
- Eliminated crawlable links to non-existent pages  
- Removed hover interaction to avoid false affordance  
- Preserved theme styling (text-muted-foreground)  
- Maintained semantic structure and visual hierarchy

title: Fix Broken Conversion UX by Removing Permanently Disabled Generate LBRN Button and Introducing Explicit State Feedback
description: Removes the permanently disabled Generate LBRN button and provides explicit state feedback to improve user experience during LBRN generation.
body:
The Generate LBRN button was always disabled because file upload triggers automatic conversion. This created a misleading UX:
- The button appeared permanently disabled.
- LBRN Generated was shown as a disabled button, implying failure instead of success.
- The UI suggested a manual action that did not actually exist.
- Users could interpret the disabled state as a bug.
